│ stop({"edit_points": [[1092, 1093, "llvm/lib/Analysis/ConstantFolding.cpp"],  │
│ [1159, 1161, "llvm/lib/Analysis/ConstantFolding.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.       │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs inside ConstantFoldConstantImpl    │
│ due to an assertion in isa<> that the pointer is non-null: \"isa<> used on a  │
│ null pointer\". This means a null Constant* is being passed into              │
│ isa<ConstantVector>(C)/isa<ConstantExpr>(C). The reproducer shows Evaluator   │
│ attempting to constant-fold a call instruction where the callee's IR          │
│ definition has a mismatched return type (the function is defined as returning │
│ void, but called as returning i32). During folding of operands, a null        │
│ Constant pointer is produced, leading to a null check assertion later when    │
│ isa<> is applied.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug logs show Evaluator   │
│ trying to evaluate the basic block and it claims the function evaluated       │
│ successfully with result 0, immediately followed by the assertion from        │
│ Casting.h. The backtrace points to ConstantFoldConstantImpl and then to       │
│ ConstantFoldConstant, invoked while folding operands for evaluation. The      │
│ first transformation point identified is ConstantFoldConstantImpl in          │
│ ConstantFolding.cpp.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nExamining                    │
│ ConstantFoldConstantImpl reveals this pattern:\n  for (const Use &OldU :      │
│ C->operands()) {\n    Constant *OldC = cast<Constant>(&OldU);\n    ...\n      │
│ }\nSimilarly, ConstantFoldInstruction uses:\n  for (const Use &OpU :          │
│ I->operands()) {\n    auto *Op = cast<Constant>(&OpU);\n    Op =              │
│ ConstantFoldConstantImpl(Op, DL, TLI, FoldedOps);\n    Ops.push_back(Op);\n   │
│ }\nThis is incorrect. A Use is not a Value; it is a wrapper around a          │
│ reference to a Value. Casting the address of a Use object (&OldU or &OpU) to  │
│ Constant* is undefined behavior and can yield invalid or null pointers. The   │
│ correct way is to get the underlying Value via Use::get() and then cast that  │
│ Value to Constant: cast<Constant>(OldU.get()). Using the wrong cast can       │
│ produce a null Constant* which later gets passed into isa<> leading to the    │
│ assertion.\n\nGiven the crash signature where isa_impl_cl<ConstantVector,     │
│ const Constant*>::doit(const Constant*) asserts Val, it matches passing a     │
│ null Constant* around due to these incorrect casts.\n\n4. Proposed Edit       │
│ Point(s):\n- Edit Point 1 (ConstantFoldConstantImpl operand folding):\n       │
│ Lines 1092-1093 in llvm/lib/Analysis/ConstantFolding.cpp\n  Replace casting   │
│ of Use to Constant via its address with casting the underlying Value:\n       │
│ From:\n    Constant *OldC = cast<Constant>(&OldU);\n  To:\n    Constant *OldC │
│ = cast<Constant>(OldU.get());\n\n- Edit Point 2 (ConstantFoldInstruction      │
│ operand folding):\n  Lines 1159-1161 in                                       │
│ llvm/lib/Analysis/ConstantFolding.cpp\n  Replace casting of Use to Constant   │
│ via its address with casting the underlying Value:\n  From:\n    for (const   │
│ Use &OpU : I->operands()) {\n      auto *Op = cast<Constant>(&OpU);\n  To:\n  │
│ for (const Use &OpU : I->operands()) {\n      auto *Op =                      │
│ cast<Constant>(OpU.get());\n\nThese fixes ensure we correctly retrieve the    │
│ Value* from the Use and safely cast to Constant*, preventing null or invalid  │
│ pointers.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by incorrect casting of Use  │
│ objects to Constant* via their addresses, producing invalid/null Constant     │
│ pointers. By using Use::get() to obtain the underlying Value and then casting │
│ to Constant, we prevent passing null into isa<> and allow                     │
│ ConstantFoldConstantImpl and ConstantFoldInstruction to operate on valid      │
│ constants. This should eliminate the assertion and allow globalopt/evaluator  │
│ to proceed correctly, including handling mismatched call return types without │
│ crashing."})                                                                  │
